\f1\b Today is the anniversary of the death of Niels Henrik David Bohr
\f2\b0  (1885-1962), 
\f0 \uc0\u55356 \u56809 \u55356 \u56816 
\f2 Danish {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physicist"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 physicist}} who made foundational contributions to understanding {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_structure"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 atomic structure}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_quantum_theory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 quantum theory}}, for which he received the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nobel Prize in Physics}} in 1922. \
\
Bohr developed the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bohr_model"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Bohr model}} of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 atom}}, in which he proposed that energy levels of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electrons}} are discrete and that the electrons revolve in stable orbits around the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_nucleus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 atomic nucleus}} but can jump from one energy level (or orbit) to another. Although the Bohr model has been supplanted by other models, its underlying principles remain valid. He conceived the principle of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complementarity_(physics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 complementarity}}: that items could be separately analysed in terms of contradictory properties, like behaving as a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave%E2%80%93particle_duality"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 wave or a stream of particles}}. The notion of complementarity dominated Bohr's thinking in both science and philosophy.\cb1 \
\cb3 \
During the 1930s, Bohr helped refugees from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nazism}}. In September 1943, word reached Bohr that he was about to be arrested by the Germans, and he fled to Sweden. From there, he was flown to Britain, where he joined the British {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tube_Alloys"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Tube Alloys}} nuclear weapons project, and was part of the British mission to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manhattan_Project"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Manhattan Project}}. After the war, Bohr called for international cooperation on nuclear energy. He was involved with the establishment of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CERN"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 CERN}} and became the first chairman of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nordic_Institute_for_Theoretical_Physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nordic Institute for Theoretical Physics}} in 1957.\
\

